## What Actually Clicked for Me

What clicked today is how many real-world cloud breaches trace back to a misunderstanding — or a misapplication — of this model.

The most common pattern I came across while researching today is the **misconfigured S3 bucket**. AWS S3 provides secure object storage by default — but it also gives customers the ability to make buckets publicly accessible if they choose to. Countless organizations have accidentally exposed sensitive data by misconfiguring S3 bucket permissions, making data that should have been private accessible to anyone on the internet.

AWS did not fail in those cases. The infrastructure was working exactly as configured. The customer configured it incorrectly — and that is the customer's responsibility under the shared model. AWS has added tools and warnings over the years to help customers catch these mistakes, but the fundamental responsibility for configuration still lies with the customer.

For OpenMRS on AWS, this has direct implications. AWS will not patch the OpenMRS application for you. AWS will not configure your security groups correctly. AWS will not manage who has access to your IAM accounts. AWS will not encrypt your database unless you configure encryption. These are all customer responsibilities — and each one is a potential source of the kind of risk I have been assessing and treating over the past two days.

