## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2019 Capital One data breach** — one of the most significant cloud security incidents on record, affecting over 100 million customers in the US and Canada. The attacker exploited a misconfigured Web Application Firewall (WAF) on Capital One's AWS environment to gain access to sensitive data stored in S3.

What made this case particularly instructive is that AWS's infrastructure was not compromised. The attacker did not break into AWS data centers or defeat AWS security controls. They exploited a configuration mistake on the customer side — a WAF that had been set up with overly permissive permissions, creating a pathway to access data that should have been protected.

Capital One was subject to significant regulatory scrutiny and paid a $80 million fine to the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency. The breach affected financial data — but the same misconfiguration pattern applies directly to healthcare environments. An OpenMRS deployment with a misconfigured security group, an overly permissive IAM role, or an unprotected S3 bucket containing patient data would present essentially the same risk — and the consequences under HIPAA would be severe.

The Capital One breach is one of the clearest real-world illustrations of what the shared responsibility model means in practice. AWS was not at fault. The customer's configuration decisions created the vulnerability. Understanding that boundary is not just a theoretical exercise — it is the difference between a secure deployment and a breach investigation.

