## Common Misconfigurations to Watch For in OpenMRS on AWS

Based on today's research, here are the misconfiguration patterns I want to make sure I address throughout this project:

| Risk Area | Common Mistake | What It Should Look Like |
|---|---|---|
| Security Groups | Allowing inbound traffic from 0.0.0.0/0 on sensitive ports | Restrict to known IP ranges; only open necessary ports |
| S3 Buckets | Public access enabled on buckets containing patient data or backups | Block all public access; use bucket policies for authorized access only |
| IAM | Root account used for day-to-day operations; no MFA on privileged accounts | Use IAM roles with least privilege; enable MFA on all accounts |
| Encryption | RDS database not encrypted at rest; S3 objects not encrypted | Enable encryption at rest for all data stores; enforce HTTPS |
| Logging | CloudTrail not enabled; logs not reviewed | Enable CloudTrail in all regions; set up alerts for suspicious activity |
| Patching | EC2 instance OS not patched regularly | Establish a patching schedule; use AWS Systems Manager for automation |

Each row in that table represents a real breach pattern. None of them are exotic or difficult to fix. They are the kinds of basic hygiene failures that the shared responsibility model places squarely in the customer's hands.

